Summer 2015

In the summer, we only have meaningful quantities of data from one game, Ebb n Flow. Of note, these are 9th grade kids.

summer.2015.lumos.df %>% count(game) %>% 
  # Add some human-readable names
  left_join(summer.2015.lumos.df %>% select(game, game_name) %>% unique(),
            by="game")

Note that the loess becomes quite flat around session 8.

plot_ebb(summer.2015.lumos.df)

So lets take means of those later sessions and see how they go! Note that we are correlating score (higher is better) with ranking (lower is better). So we expect a negative correlation for the classic effect.

cog_means <- summer.2015.lumos.df %>% filter(game == 107, session >= 8) %>% group_by(KKIid) %>%
                summarise_at(vars(game_lpi), mean) 

# a simple rank-correlation
mycor <- function(x,y) {
    cor(x,y, use='na.or.complete', method="kendall")
}

left_join(summer.2015.academic.df, cog_means, by='KKIid') %>% 
    group_by(day)  %>% 
    summarize(Total=mycor(Total, game_lpi),
              English=mycor(English, game_lpi),
              Math=mycor(Math, game_lpi),
              Special=mycor(Special, game_lpi)) %>%
    gather(key=Subject, value=Correlation, -day) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=day, y=Correlation, color=Subject)) + geom_line()

Hmm

Summer 2016

Our main 2016 sample is 8th graders. This session was run a little better, and kids were able to also play a game based on the classic flanker task (attentional control focus).

summer.2016.lumos.df %>% count(game) %>% arrange(-n) %>% head() %>% 
  # Again, add human-readable names
  left_join(summer.2016.lumos.df %>% select(game, game_name) %>% unique(),
            by='game')

summer.2016.lumos.df %>% filter(game %in% c(107, 109)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=session, y=game_lpi)) +
    geom_line(aes(group=KKIid), alpha=0.2) +
    stat_smooth(method='lm', color='red') +
    stat_smooth(method='loess') +
    facet_wrap(~ game)
